               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390708-name-154" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390708-name-154" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390708-name-154" type="surname" value="MILES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390708-name-154" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE MILES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a gardener, and live in Cooper's-place, Quebec-street. The prisoner is my daughter—she had left my house—I lost a pair of shears on Friday, the 28th of June—the prisoner was on the landing that morning as I went out to work—I got information, and went to Hoperoft's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390708-name-155" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390708-name-155" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390708-name-155" type="surname" value="HOPCROFT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390708-name-155" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA HOPCROFT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a dealer in marine stores, in Little York-place. The prisoner brought a pair of shears to me last Friday week—I have known her and her father some time—she said her father had sent her—I gave her 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for them—I considered that the full value—they are rusty, and have no handle—I bought them as old iron—I told her I could only buy them as old iron—I did then know her father was a gardener—I thought he had sent her to raise 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I knew him to be very poor, and considered they were of no use.</p>
               <p>
